# {{obsolete}} [[back|Back]] in the reverse direction, or to an original starting point. {{defdate|10th-18th c.}}
#* '''1526''', ''The Bible'', tr. William Tyndale, Matthew 2:
#*: And after they were warned in ther slepe, that they shulde not go '''ageyne''' to Herod, they retourned into ther awne countre another way.
# [[back|Back]] (to a former place or state). {{defdate|from 11th c.}}
#: ''We need to bring the old customs to life '''again'''.''
#: ''The South will rise '''again'''.''
# {{obsolete}} [[in return|In return]], as a reciprocal action; [[back]]. {{defdate|13th-19th c.}}
#* '''1485''', Sir Thomas Malory, ''Le Morte Darthur'', Book III:
#*: Merlyn warned the kynge couertly that gweneuer was not holsome for hym to take to wyf, for he warned hym that launcelot shold loue her and she hym '''ageyne''' {{...}}
#*:: Merlin warned the king covertly that Guinevere was not wholesome for him to take as his wife, for he warned him that Lancelot should love her and she him '''again''' {{...}}
#* '''1621''', Robert Burton, ''The Anatomy of Melancholy'', I.2.4.vii:
#*: Thus men are plagued with women, they '''again''' with men, when they are of diverse humours and conditions [...].
# Another time; once more. {{defdate|from 14th c.}}
#: ''I didn't do a very good job the first time, and now I have to do it '''again'''.''
#* '''1979''', Charles Edward Daniels et al., “The Devil Went Down to Georgia” (song), ''Million Mile Reflections'', Charlie Daniels Band, Epic Records:
#*: Johnny said, “Devil, just come on back if you ever want to try '''again'''. {{...}}”
# Over and above a factor of one. {{defdate|from 16th c.}}
#* '''1908''' December 10, Austin H. Clark, “New Genera and Species of Crinoids”, ''Proceedings of the Biological Society of Washington'', Volume XXI, [http://books.google.com/books?id=uc7RAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA229&dq=again pages 229-230]:
#*: Cirri <span style="font-variant:small-caps">l-lxxx</span>, 15, about 12mm. long; first two joints short, about twice as broad as long; third about one-third '''again''' [=one and one-third times] as long as broad; fourth and fifth the longest, about half '''again''' [=one and a half times] as long as broad; {{...}}
# {{non-gloss definition|Used metalinguistically, with the repetition being in the discussion, or in the linguistic or pragmatic context of the discussion, rather than in the subject of discussion.}} {{defdate|from 16th c.}}
#: ''Great, thanks '''again'''!''
## Tell me again, say again; {{non-gloss definition|used in asking a question to which one may have already received the answer, but cannot remember it.}}
##: ''What's that called, '''again'''?''
## I ask again, I say again; {{non-gloss definition|used in repeating a question or statement.}}
##: '''''Again''', as I said before, I'm not criticizing, I just want to understand.''
## Here too, here also, in this case as well; {{non-gloss definition|used in applying a previously made point to a new instance; sometimes preceded by "here".}}
##: ''Approach B is better than approach A in many respects, but '''again''', there are difficulties in implementing it.''

